# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: proximity-sensors
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:proximity-sensors/capacitive-displacement-sensor] where $\varepsilon _{0}$ is the permittivity of free space constant and *$\varepsilon _{r}$* is the relative permittivity (also called the dielectric constant) of the material in the gap.
[src:proximity-sensors/capacitive-displacement-sensor] There are two general types of capacitive displacement sensing systems.
[src:proximity-sensors/capacitive-displacement-sensor] One type is used to measure the thicknesses of conductive materials.
[src:proximity-sensors/capacitive-displacement-sensor] The other type measures the thickness of non-conductive materials or the level of a fluid.
[src:proximity-sensors/capacitive-displacement-sensor] A capacitive sensing system for conductive materials uses a model similar to the one described above, but in place of one of the conductive plates is the sensor, and in place of the other is the conductive target to be measured.
[src:proximity-sensors/capacitive-displacement-sensor] where α indicates a proportional relationship.
[src:proximity-sensors/capacitive-displacement-sensor] Due to this proportional relationship, a capacitive sensing system is able to measure changes in capacitance and translate these changes into distance measurements.
[src:proximity-sensors/capacitive-displacement-sensor] The operation of the sensor for measuring the thickness of non-conductive materials can be thought of as two capacitors in series, with each having a different dielectric (and dielectric constant).
[src:proximity-sensors/capacitive-displacement-sensor] The sum of the thicknesses of the two dielectric materials remains constant but the thickness of each can vary.
[src:proximity-sensors/capacitive-displacement-sensor] The thickness of the material to be measured displaces the other dielectric.
[src:proximity-sensors/capacitive-displacement-sensor] The gap is often an air gap (*$\varepsilon _{r}$*≈1) and the material has a higher dielectric.
[src:proximity-sensors/capacitive-displacement-sensor] As the material gets thicker, the capacitance increases and is sensed by the system.
[src:proximity-sensors/capacitive-displacement-sensor] A sensor for measuring fluid levels works as two capacitors in parallel with a constant total area.
[src:proximity-sensors/capacitive-displacement-sensor] Again the difference in the dielectric constant of the fluid and the dielectric constant of air results in detectable changes in the capacitance between the conductive probes or plates.
[src:proximity-sensors/capacitive-displacement-sensor] One of the more common applications of capacitive sensors is for precision positioning.
[src:proximity-sensors/capacitive-displacement-sensor] Capacitive displacement sensors can be used to measure the position of objects down to the nanometer level.
[src:proximity-sensors/capacitive-displacement-sensor] This type of precise positioning is used in the semiconductor industry where silicon wafers need to be positioned for exposure.
[src:proximity-sensors/capacitive-displacement-sensor] Capacitive sensors are also used to pre-focus the electron microscopes used in testing and examining the wafers.
[src:proximity-sensors/capacitive-displacement-sensor] In the disc drive industry, capacitive displacement sensors are used to measure the runout (a measure of how much the axis of rotation deviates from an ideal fixed line) of disc drives spindles.
[src:proximity-sensors/capacitive-displacement-sensor] By knowing the exact runout of these spindles, disc drive manufacturers are able to determine the maximum amount of data that can be placed onto the drives.
[src:proximity-sensors/capacitive-displacement-sensor] Capacitive sensors are also used to ensure that disc drive platters are orthogonal to the spindle before data is written to them.
[src:proximity-sensors/capacitive-displacement-sensor] Capacitive displacement sensors can be used to make very precise thickness measurements.
[src:proximity-sensors/capacitive-displacement-sensor] Capacitive displacement sensors operate by measuring changes in position.
[src:proximity-sensors/capacitive-displacement-sensor] If the position of a reference part of known thickness is measured, other parts can be subsequently measured and the differences in position can be used to determine the thickness of these parts.
[src:proximity-sensors/capacitive-displacement-sensor] In order for this to be effective using a single probe, the parts must be completely flat and measured on a perfectly flat surface.
[src:proximity-sensors/capacitive-displacement-sensor] If the part to be measured has any curvature or deformity, or simply does not rest firmly against the flat surface, the distance between the part to be measured and the surface it is placed upon will be erroneously included in the thickness measurement.
[src:proximity-sensors/capacitive-displacement-sensor] This error can be eliminated by using two capacitive sensors to measure a single part.
[src:proximity-sensors/capacitive-displacement-sensor] Capacitive sensors are placed on either side of the part to be measured.
[src:proximity-sensors/capacitive-displacement-sensor] By measuring the parts from both sides, curvature and deformities are taken into account in the measurement and their effects are not included in the thickness readings.
[src:proximity-sensors/capacitive-displacement-sensor] The thickness of plastic materials can be measured with the material placed between two electrodes a set distance apart.
[src:proximity-sensors/capacitive-displacement-sensor] The plastic when placed between the electrodes acts as a dielectric and displaces air (which has a dielectric constant of 1, different from the plastic).
[src:proximity-sensors/capacitive-displacement-sensor] Consequently, the capacitance between the electrodes changes.
[src:proximity-sensors/capacitive-displacement-sensor] The capacitance changes can then be measured and correlated with the material's thickness.
[src:proximity-sensors/capacitive-displacement-sensor] Capacitive sensor circuits can be constructed that are able to detect changes in capacitance on the order of 10−5 picofarads (10 attofarads).
[src:proximity-sensors/capacitive-displacement-sensor] While capacitive displacement sensors are most often used to sense changes in position of conductive targets, they can also be used to sense the thickness and/or density of non-conductive targets as well.
[src:proximity-sensors/capacitive-displacement-sensor] A non-conductive object placed in between the probe and conductive target will have a different dielectric constant than the air in the gap and will therefore change the Capacitance between probe and target.
[src:proximity-sensors/capacitive-displacement-sensor] (See the first equation above) By analyzing this change in capacitance, the thickness and density of the non-conductor can be determined.
[src:proximity-sensors/capacitive-displacement-sensor] Capacitive displacement sensors are often used in metrology applications.
[src:proximity-sensors/capacitive-displacement-sensor] In many cases, sensors are used “to measure shape errors in the part being produced.
[src:proximity-sensors/capacitive-displacement-sensor] But they also can measure the errors arising in the equipment used to manufacture the part, a practice known as machine tool metrology”.
[src:proximity-sensors/capacitive-displacement-sensor] In many cases, the sensors are used to analyze and optimize the rotation of spindles in various machine tools, examples include surface grinders, lathes, milling machines, and air bearing spindles.
[src:proximity-sensors/capacitive-displacement-sensor] By measuring errors in the machines themselves, rather than simply measuring errors in the final products, problems can be dealt with and fixed earlier in the manufacturing process.
[src:proximity-sensors/capacitive-displacement-sensor] Capacitive displacement sensors are often used in assembly line testing.
[src:proximity-sensors/capacitive-displacement-sensor] Sometimes they are used to test assembled parts for uniformity, thickness or other design features.
[src:proximity-sensors/capacitive-displacement-sensor] At other times, they are used to simply look for the presence or absence of a certain component, such as glue.
[src:proximity-sensors/capacitive-displacement-sensor] Using capacitive sensors to test assembly line parts can help to prevent quality concerns further along in the production process.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] A **passive infrared sensor** (**PIR sensor**) is an electronic device that measures infrared (IR) radiation emitted by objects in its field of view.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] They are most commonly used in motion detectors, including security alarms and automatic lighting systems.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] PIR sensors detect general movement but do not provide information on the source of motion; for that purpose, an imaging IR sensor is required.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] PIR sensors are often referred to simply as "PIR", or sometimes "PID" (passive infrared detector).
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] The term "passive" indicates that the device does not emit energy, but detects infrared radiation (heat) emitted or reflected by objects.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] All objects with a temperature above absolute zero emit heat energy in the form of electromagnetic radiation.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] Usually this radiation isn't visible to the human eye because it radiates at infrared wavelengths, but it can be detected by electronic devices designed for such a purpose.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] A PIR-based motion detector is used to sense movement of people, animals, or other objects.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] They are commonly used in burglar alarms and automatically activated lighting systems.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] A PIR sensor detects changes in the amount of infrared radiation impinging upon it, which varies depending on the temperature and surface characteristics of objects in its field of view.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] When an object, such as a person, passes in front of a background (e.g. a wall), the temperature at that point rises from room temperature to body temperature and then returns.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] The sensor converts this change in infrared radiation into a change in output voltage, triggering detection.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] Objects of similar temperature but different surface characteristics may also produce different infrared emission patterns, and movement relative to the background may likewise trigger the detector.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] PIRs come in various configurations for different applications.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] Common models use multiple Fresnel lenses or mirror segments, have an effective range of about 10 metres (30 feet), and a field of view of less than 180°.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] Models with wider fields of view, including 360°, are also available, typically for ceiling mounting.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] Some larger PIRs use single-segment mirrors and can detect changes in infrared energy over distances exceeding 30 metres (100 feet).
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] There are also designs with reversible orientation mirrors, allowing either broad coverage (around 110°) or narrow "curtain" coverage, as well as models with individually selectable segments to shape the coverage.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] Pairs of sensor elements may be wired as opposite inputs to a differential amplifier.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] In this configuration, the PIR signals cancel each other, removing the average temperature of the field of view from the output; an increase of IR energy across the entire sensor is self-cancelling and will not trigger the device.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] This helps reduce false detections caused by brief flashes of light or field-wide illumination (although sustained high energy exposure may still saturate the sensor).
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] The differential arrangement also reduces common-mode interference, making the device less sensitive to nearby electric fields.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] However, in this configuration, the sensor cannot measure absolute temperature and is therefore used only for motion detection.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] When a PIR sensor is configured in a differential mode, it specifically becomes applicable as a motion detector device.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] In this mode, when a movement is detected within the "line of sight" of the sensor, a pair of complementary pulses are processed at the output pin of the sensor.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] In order to implement this output signal for a practical triggering of a load such as a relay or a data logger, or an alarm, the differential signal is rectified using a bridge rectifier and fed to a transistorized relay driver circuit.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] The contacts of this relay close and open in response to the signals from the PIR, activating the attached load across its contacts, acknowledging the detection of a person within the predetermined restricted area.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] The PIR sensor is typically mounted on a printed circuit board containing the necessary electronics required to interpret the signals from the sensor itself.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] The complete assembly is usually contained within a housing, mounted in a location where the sensor can cover the area to be monitored.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] The housing will usually have a plastic "window" through which the infrared energy can enter.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] Despite often being only translucent to visible light, infrared energy is able to reach the sensor through the window because the plastic used is transparent to infrared radiation.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] The plastic window reduces the chance of foreign objects (dust, insects, rain, etc.) from obscuring the sensor's field of view, damaging the mechanism, and/or causing false alarms.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] The window may be used as a filter, to limit the wavelengths to 8–14 micrometres, which is closest to the infrared radiation emitted by humans.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] It may also serve as a focusing mechanism; see below.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] Different mechanisms can be used to focus the distant infrared energy onto the sensor surface.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] The plastic window covering may have multiple facets molded into it, to focus the infrared energy onto the sensor.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] Each individual facet is a Fresnel lens.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] Some PIRs are manufactured with internal, segmented parabolic mirrors to focus the infrared energy.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] Where mirrors are used, the plastic window cover generally has no Fresnel lenses molded into it.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] As a result of the focussing, the detector view is actually a beam pattern.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] Under certain angles (zones), the PIR sensor receives almost no radiation energy and under other angles the PIR receives concentrated amounts of infrared energy.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] This separation helps the motion detector to discriminate between field-wide illumination and moving objects.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] When a person walks from one angle (beam) to another, the detector will only intermittently see the moving person.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] This results in a rapidly changing sensor signal which is used by the electronics to trigger an alarm or to turn on lighting.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] A slowly changing signal will be ignored by the electronics.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] The number, shape, distribution and sensitivity of these zones are determined by the lens and/or mirror.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] Manufacturers do their best to create the optimal sensitivity beam pattern for each application.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] When used as part of a lighting system, the electronics in the PIR typically control an integral relay capable of switching mains voltage.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] This means the PIR can be set up to turn on lights that are connected to the PIR when movement is detected.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] This is most commonly used in outdoor scenarios either to deter criminals (security lighting) or for practical uses like the front door light turning on so you can find your keys in the dark.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] Additional uses can be in public toilets, walk-in pantries, hallways or anywhere that automatic control of lights is useful.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] This can provide energy savings as the lights are only turned on when they are needed and there is no reliance on users remembering to turn the lights off when they leave the area.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] When used as part of a security system, the electronics in the PIR typically control a small relay.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] This relay completes the circuit across a pair of electrical contacts connected to a detection input zone of the burglar alarm control panel.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] The system is usually designed such that if no motion is being detected, the relay contact is closed—a 'normally closed' (NC) relay.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] If motion is detected, the relay will open the circuit, triggering the alarm; or, if a wire is disconnected, the alarm will also operate.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] Manufacturers recommend careful placement of their products to prevent false alarms (i.e., any detection not caused by an intruder).
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] They suggest mounting the PIRs in such a way that the PIR cannot "see" out of a window.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] Although the wavelength of infrared radiation to which the chips are sensitive does not penetrate glass very well, a strong infrared source (such as from a vehicle headlight or sunlight) can overload the sensor and cause a false alarm.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] A person moving on the other side of the glass would not be "seen" by the PID.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] That may be good for a window facing a public sidewalk, or bad for a window in an interior partition.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] It is also recommended that the PIR not be placed in such a position that an HVAC vent would blow hot or cold air onto the surface of the plastic which covers the housing's window.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] Although air has very low emissivity (emits very small amounts of infrared energy), the air blowing on the plastic window cover could change the plastic's temperature enough to trigger a false alarm.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] Sensors are also often designed to "ignore" domestic pets, such as dogs or cats, by setting a higher sensitivity threshold, or by ensuring that the floor of the room remains out of focus.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] Since PIR sensors have ranges of up to 10 meters (30 feet), a single detector placed near the entrance is typically all that is necessary for rooms with only a single entrance.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] PIR-based security systems are also viable in outdoor security and motion-sensitive lighting; one advantage is their low power draw, which allows them to be solar-powered.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] Designs have been implemented in which a PIR circuit measures the temperature of a remote object.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] In such a circuit, a non-differential PIR output is used.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] The output signal is evaluated according to a calibration for the IR spectrum of a specific type of matter to be observed.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] By this means, relatively accurate and precise temperature measurements may be obtained remotely.
[src:proximity-sensors/passive-infrared-sensor] Without calibration to the type of material being observed, a PIR thermometer device is able to measure changes in IR emission which correspond directly to temperature changes, but the actual temperature values cannot be calculated.
[src:proximity-sensors/photoelectric-sensor] A **photoelectric sensor** is a device used to determine the distance, absence, or presence of an object by using a light transmitter, often infrared, and a photoelectric receiver.
[src:proximity-sensors/photoelectric-sensor] They are largely used in industrial manufacturing.
[src:proximity-sensors/photoelectric-sensor] There are three different useful types: opposed (through-beam), retro-reflective, and proximity-sensing (diffused).
[src:proximity-sensors/photoelectric-sensor] A self-contained photoelectric sensor contains the optics, along with the electronics.
[src:proximity-sensors/photoelectric-sensor] The sensor performs its own modulation, demodulation, amplification, and output switching.
[src:proximity-sensors/photoelectric-sensor] Some self-contained sensors provide such options as built-in control timers or counters.
[src:proximity-sensors/photoelectric-sensor] Because of technological progress, self-contained photoelectric sensors have become increasingly smaller.
[src:proximity-sensors/photoelectric-sensor] Remote photoelectric sensors used for remote sensing contain only the optical components of a sensor.
[src:proximity-sensors/photoelectric-sensor] The circuitry for power input, amplification, and output switching is located elsewhere, typically in a control panel.
[src:proximity-sensors/photoelectric-sensor] This allows the sensor, itself, to be very small.
[src:proximity-sensors/photoelectric-sensor] Also, the controls for the sensor are more accessible, since they may be bigger.
[src:proximity-sensors/photoelectric-sensor] When space is restricted or the environment too hostile even for remote sensors, fibre optics may be used.
[src:proximity-sensors/photoelectric-sensor] Fibre optics are passive mechanical sensing components.
[src:proximity-sensors/photoelectric-sensor] They may be used with either remote or self-contained sensors.
[src:proximity-sensors/photoelectric-sensor] They have no electrical circuitry and no moving parts, and can safely pipe light into and out of hostile environments.
[src:proximity-sensors/photoelectric-sensor] A through-beam arrangement consists of a receiver located within the line-of-sight of the transmitter.
[src:proximity-sensors/photoelectric-sensor] In this mode, an object is detected when the light beam is blocked from getting to the receiver from the transmitter.
[src:proximity-sensors/photoelectric-sensor] A retroreflective arrangement places the transmitter and receiver at the same location and uses a reflector to bounce the inverted light beam back from the transmitter to the receiver.
[src:proximity-sensors/photoelectric-sensor] An object is sensed when the beam is interrupted and fails to reach the receiver.
[src:proximity-sensors/photoelectric-sensor] A proximity-sensing (diffused) arrangement is one in which the transmitted radiation must reflect off the object in order to reach the receiver.
[src:proximity-sensors/photoelectric-sensor] In this mode, an object is detected when the receiver sees the transmitted source rather than when it fails to see it.
[src:proximity-sensors/photoelectric-sensor] As in retro-reflective sensors, diffuse sensor emitters and receivers are located in the same housing.
[src:proximity-sensors/photoelectric-sensor] But the target acts as the reflector so that detection of light is reflected off the disturbance object.
[src:proximity-sensors/photoelectric-sensor] The emitter sends out a beam of light (most often a pulsed infrared, visible red, or laser) that diffuses in all directions, filling a detection area.
[src:proximity-sensors/photoelectric-sensor] The target then enters the area and deflects part of the beam back to the receiver.
[src:proximity-sensors/photoelectric-sensor] Detection occurs and output is turned on or off when sufficient light falls on the receiver.
[src:proximity-sensors/photoelectric-sensor] Some photo-eyes have two different operational types, light operate and dark operate.
[src:proximity-sensors/photoelectric-sensor] The light operates photo eyes become operational when the receiver "receives" the transmitter signal.
[src:proximity-sensors/photoelectric-sensor] Dark operate photo eyes become operational when the receiver "does not receive" the transmitter signal.
[src:proximity-sensors/photoelectric-sensor] The detecting range of a photoelectric sensor is its "field of view", or the maximum distance from which the sensor can retrieve information, minus the minimum distance.
[src:proximity-sensors/photoelectric-sensor] A minimum detectable object is the smallest object the sensor can detect.
[src:proximity-sensors/photoelectric-sensor] More accurate sensors can often have minimum detectable objects of minuscule size.
[src:proximity-sensors/proximity-sensor] A **proximity sensor** (often simply **prox**) is a sensor able to detect the presence of nearby objects without any physical contact.
[src:proximity-sensors/proximity-sensor] A proximity sensor often emits an electromagnetic field or a beam of electromagnetic radiation (infrared, for instance), and looks for changes in the field or return signal.
[src:proximity-sensors/proximity-sensor] The object being sensed is often referred to as the proximity sensor's target.
[src:proximity-sensors/proximity-sensor] Different proximity sensor targets demand different sensors.
[src:proximity-sensors/proximity-sensor] For example, a capacitive proximity sensor or photoelectric sensor might be suitable for a plastic target; an inductive proximity sensor always requires a metal target.
[src:proximity-sensors/proximity-sensor] Proximity sensors can have a high reliability and long functional life because of the absence of mechanical parts and lack of physical contact between the sensor and the sensed object.
[src:proximity-sensors/proximity-sensor] Proximity sensors are also used in machine vibration monitoring to measure the variation in distance between a shaft and its support bearing.
[src:proximity-sensors/proximity-sensor] This is common in large steam turbines, compressors, and motors that use sleeve-type bearings.
[src:proximity-sensors/proximity-sensor] A proximity sensor adjusted to a very short range is often used as a touch switch.
[src:proximity-sensors/proximity-sensor] Proximity sensors are commonly used on mobile devices.
[src:proximity-sensors/proximity-sensor] When the target is within nominal range, the device lock screen user interface will appear, thus emerging from what is known as sleep mode.
[src:proximity-sensors/proximity-sensor] Once the device has awoken from sleep mode, if the proximity sensor's target is still for an extended period of time, the sensor will then ignore it, and the device will eventually revert into sleep mode.
[src:proximity-sensors/proximity-sensor] For example, during a telephone call, proximity sensors play a role in detecting (and skipping) accidental touchscreen taps when mobiles are held to the ear.
[src:proximity-sensors/proximity-sensor] Proximity sensors can be used to recognise air gestures and hover-manipulations.
[src:proximity-sensors/proximity-sensor] An array of proximity sensing elements can replace vision-camera or depth camera based solutions for hand gesture detection.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] Laser-based time-of-flight cameras are part of a broader class of scannerless LIDAR, in which the entire scene is captured with each laser pulse, as opposed to point-by-point with a laser beam such as in scanning LIDAR systems.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] Time-of-flight camera products for civil applications began to emerge around 2000, as the semiconductor processes allowed the production of components fast enough for such devices.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] The systems cover ranges of a few centimeters up to several kilometers.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] Several different technologies for time-of-flight cameras have been developed.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] Photonic Mixer Devices (PMD), the Swiss Ranger, and CanestaVision work by modulating the outgoing beam with an RF carrier, then measuring the phase shift of that carrier on the receiver side.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] This approach has a modular error challenge: measured ranges are modulo the RF carrier wavelength.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] The Swiss Ranger is a compact, short-range device, with ranges of 5 or 10 meters and a resolution of 176 x 144 pixels.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] With phase unwrapping algorithms, the maximum uniqueness range can be increased.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] Illumination is pulsed LEDs rather than a laser.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] More recent CW-ToF camera systems illuminate the scene with high-frequency modulated LED light and analyze the phase shift of the returning signal at each pixel to compute depth.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] For example, in traffic enforcement applications, retroreflective surfaces such as license plates and vehicle reflectors generate strong return signals that are used to construct depth images over time.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] These images allow tracking of vehicle positions in 3D space and calculation of speed by applying regression analysis to the position-time data.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] Unlike conventional RADAR, this method measures speed along the vehicle's true direction of travel and is independent of the vehicle’s distance and angle relative to the camera.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] In some continuous-wave ToF systems, depth images captured over successive time intervals are used to estimate the 3D positions of moving objects, such as vehicles.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] The system tracks multiple retroreflective points across consecutive frames and reconstructs the object’s trajectory through 3D space.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] By applying regression analysis to the change in position over time, the system accurately determines the object's speed along its path of travel.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] Unlike conventional RADAR, this approach minimizes errors associated with distance and angle to the target.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] CanestaVision developer Canesta was purchased by Microsoft in 2010.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] The Kinect2 for Xbox One was based on ToF technology from Canesta.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] These devices have a built-in shutter in the image sensor that opens and closes at the same rate as the light pulses are sent out.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] Most time-of-flight 3D sensors are based on this principle invented by Medina.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] Because part of every returning pulse is blocked by the shutter according to its time of arrival, the amount of light received relates to the distance the pulse has traveled.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] The distance can be calculated using the equation, *z* = *R* (*S2* − *S1*) / 2(*S1* + *S2*) + *R* / 2 for an ideal camera.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] *R* is the camera range, determined by the round trip of the light pulse, *S1* the amount of the light pulse that is received, and *S2* the amount of the light pulse that is blocked.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] The ZCam by 3DV Systems is a range-gated system.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] Microsoft's second-generation Kinect sensor was developed using knowledge gained from Canesta and 3DV Systems.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] Similar principles are used in the ToF camera line developed by the Fraunhofer Institute of Microelectronic Circuits and Systems and TriDiCam.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] These cameras employ photodetectors with a fast electronic shutter.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] The depth resolution of ToF cameras can be improved with ultra-fast gating intensified CCD cameras.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] These cameras provide gating times down to 200ps and enable ToF setup with sub-millimeter depth resolution.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] Range gated imagers can also be used in 2D imaging to suppress anything outside a specified distance range, such as to see through fog.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] A pulsed laser provides illumination, and an optical gate allows light to reach the imager only during the desired time period.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] These devices measure the direct time-of-flight required for a single laser pulse to leave the camera and reflect back onto the focal plane array.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] Also known as "trigger mode", the 3D images captured using this methodology image complete spatial and temporal data, recording full 3D scenes with single laser pulse.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] This allows rapid acquisition and rapid real-time processing of scene information.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] For time-sensitive autonomous operations, this approach has been demonstrated for autonomous space testing and operation such as used on the OSIRIS-REx Bennu asteroid sample and return mission and autonomous helicopter landing.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] Advanced Scientific Concepts, Inc. provides application specific (e.g. aerial, automotive, space) Direct TOF vision systems known as 3D Flash LIDAR cameras.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] Their approach utilizes InGaAs Avalanche Photo Diode (APD) or PIN photodetector arrays capable of imaging laser pulse in the 980 nm to 1600 nm wavelengths.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] The simplest version of a time-of-flight camera uses *light pulses* or a single light pulse.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] The illumination is switched on for a very short time, the resulting light pulse illuminates the scene and is reflected by the objects in the field of view.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] The camera lens gathers the reflected light and images it onto the sensor or focal plane array.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] Depending upon the distance, the incoming light experiences a delay.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] For amplitude modulated arrays, the pulse width of the illumination determines the maximum range the camera can handle.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] These short times show that the illumination unit is a critical part of the system.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] Only with special LEDs or lasers is it possible to generate such short pulses.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] The single pixel consists of a photo sensitive element (e.g. a photo diode).
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] It converts the incoming light into a current.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] In analog timing imagers, connected to the photo diode are fast switches, which direct the current to one of two (or several) memory elements (e.g. a capacitor) that act as summation elements.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] In digital timing imagers, a time counter, that can be running at several gigahertz, is connected to each photodetector pixel and stops counting when light is sensed.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] In the diagram of an amplitude modulated array analog timer, the pixel uses two switches (G1 and G2) and two memory elements (S1 and S2).
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] The switches are controlled by a pulse with the same length as the light pulse, where the control signal of switch G2 is delayed by exactly the pulse width.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] Depending on the delay, only part of the light pulse is sampled through G1 in S1, the other part is stored in S2.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] Depending on the distance, the ratio between S1 and S2 changes as depicted in the drawing.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] Because only small amounts of light hit the sensor within 50 ns, not only one but several thousand pulses are sent out (repetition rate tR) and gathered, thus increasing the signal-to-noise ratio.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] After the exposure, the pixel is read out and the following stages measure the signals S1 and S2.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] In the example, the signals have the following values: S1 = 0.66 and S2 = 0.33.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] In the presence of background light the memory elements receive an additional part of the signal.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] This would disturb the distance measurement.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] To eliminate the background part of the signal, the whole measurement can be performed a second time with the illumination switched off.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] If the objects are further away than the distance range, the result is also wrong.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] Here, a second measurement with the control signals delayed by an additional pulse width helps to suppress such objects.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] Other systems work with a sinusoidally modulated light source instead of the pulse source.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] For direct TOF imagers, such as 3D Flash LIDAR, a single short pulse from 5 to 10 ns is emitted by the laser.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] The T-zero event (the time the pulse leaves the camera) is established by capturing the pulse directly and routing this timing onto the focal plane array.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] T-zero is used to compare the return time of the returning reflected pulse on the various pixels of the focal plane array.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] By comparing T-zero and the captured returned pulse and comparing the time difference, each pixel accurately outputs a direct time-of-flight measurement.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] The round trip of a single pulse for 100 meters is 660 ns.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] With a 10 ns pulse, the scene is illuminated and the range and intensity captured in less than 1 microsecond.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] In contrast to stereo vision or triangulation systems, the whole system is very compact: the illumination is placed just next to the lens, whereas the other systems need a certain minimum base line.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] In contrast to laser scanning systems, no mechanical moving parts are needed.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] It is a direct process to extract the distance information out of the output signals of the TOF sensor.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] As a result, this task uses only a small amount of processing power, again in contrast to stereo vision, where complex correlation algorithms are implemented.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] After the distance data has been extracted, object detection, for example, is also a straightforward process to carry out because the algorithms are not disturbed by patterns on the object.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] The accuracy is usually estimated at 1% of the measured distance.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] Time-of-flight cameras are able to measure the distances within a complete scene with a single shot.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] As the cameras reach up to 160 frames per second, they are ideally suited to be used in real-time applications.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] When using CMOS or other integrating detectors or sensors that use visible or near infra-red light (400 nm - 700 nm), although most of the background light coming from artificial lighting or the sun is suppressed, the pixel still has to provide a high dynamic range.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] The background light also generates electrons, which have to be stored.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] For example, the illumination units in many of today's TOF cameras can provide an illumination level of about 1 watt.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] The Sun has an illumination power of about 1050 watts per square meter, and 50 watts after the optical band-pass filter.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] Therefore, if the illuminated scene has a size of 1 square meter, the light from the sun is 50 times stronger than the modulated signal.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] Such TOF sensors are used in space applications and in consideration for automotive applications.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] In certain types of TOF devices (but not all of them), if several time-of-flight cameras are running at the same time, the TOF cameras may disturb each other's measurements.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] For Direct TOF type cameras that use a single laser pulse for illumination, because the single laser pulse is short (e.g.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] 10 nanoseconds), the round trip TOF to and from the objects in the field of view is correspondingly short (e.g.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] For an imager capturing at 30 Hz, the probability of an interfering interaction is the time that the camera acquisition gate is open divided by the time between laser pulses or approximately 1 in 50,000 (0.66 μs divided by 33 ms).
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] In contrast to laser scanning systems where a single point is illuminated, the time-of-flight cameras illuminate a whole scene.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] For a phase difference device (amplitude modulated array), due to multiple reflections, the light may reach the objects along several paths.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] Therefore, the measured distance may be greater than the true distance.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] Direct TOF imagers are vulnerable if the light is reflecting from a specular surface.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] There are published papers available that outline the strengths and weaknesses of the various TOF devices and approaches.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] Time-of-flight cameras are used for a wide variety of applications.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] Examples include robotics and touchless user interfaces.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] Continuous-wave ToF systems are used to detect retroreflective surfaces such as license plates and vehicle reflectors.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] These systems capture a sequence of depth images to track vehicle positions in 3D space over time.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] By analyzing the trajectory of these points, they can accurately calculate the speed of vehicles, independently of the distance and angle between the vehicle and the camera.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] Time-of-flight cameras are used in assistance and safety functions for advanced automotive applications such as active pedestrian safety, precrash detection and indoor applications like out-of-position (OOP) detection.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] As time-of-flight cameras provide distance images in real time, it is easy to track movements of humans.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] This allows new interactions with consumer devices such as televisions.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] Another topic is to use this type of cameras to interact with games on video game consoles.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] The second-generation Kinect sensor originally included with the Xbox One console used a time-of-flight camera for its range imaging, enabling natural user interfaces and gaming applications using computer vision and gesture recognition techniques.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] Creative and Intel also provide a similar type of interactive gesture time-of-flight camera for gaming, the Senz3D based on the DepthSense 325 camera of Softkinetic.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] Infineon and PMD Technologies enable tiny integrated 3D depth cameras for close-range gesture control of consumer devices like all-in-one PCs and laptops (Picco flexx and Picco monstar cameras).
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] Several smartphones include time-of-flight cameras.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] These are mainly used to improve the quality of photos by providing the camera software with information about foreground and background.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] The first mobile phone released with such technology was the LG G3, from early 2014.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] The BlackBerry Passport and the LG G Flex 2 were also launched with a ToF sensor.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] Other applications are measurement tasks, e.g. for the fill height in silos.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] In industrial machine vision, the time-of-flight camera helps to classify and locate objects for use by robots, such as items passing by on a conveyor.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] Door controls can distinguish easily between animals and humans reaching the door.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] Another use of these cameras is the field of robotics: Mobile robots can build up a map of their surroundings very quickly, enabling them to avoid obstacles or follow a leading person.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] As the distance calculation is simple, only little computational power is used.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] Since these cameras can also be used to measure distance, teams for FIRST Robotics Competition have been known to use the devices for autonomous routines.
[src:proximity-sensors/time-of-flight-camera] ToF cameras have been used to obtain digital elevation models of the Earth's surface topography, for studies in geomorphology.
